title: CRCM5-CMIP6 : Canadian Regional Climate Model v.5 - CMIP6 : hourly
institution: Ouranos Consortium on Regional Climatology and Adaptation to Climate Change
abstract: Ouranos produces operational regional climate simulations over the Cordex North American domain, at 0.11° resolution. The current ensemble uses the fifth version of the CRCM, developed at UQAM's ESCER center in collaboration with ECCC. Pilot data for the simulations come from the CMIP6 ensemble, except for those in hindcast mode, which use ERA5.
license: Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International Public License: https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/legalcode

title: ESPO-R5 v1.0.0 : Ouranos Multipurpose Regional Climate Scenarios
institution: Ouranos Consortium on Regional Climatology and Adaptation to Climate Change
abstract: The need to adapt to climate change is present in a growing number of fields, leading to an increase in the demand for climate scenarios for often interrelated sectors of activity. In order to meet this growing demand and to ensure the availability of climate scenarios responding to numerous vulnerability, impact and adaptation (VIA) studies, Ouranos is working to create a set of operational multipurpose climate scenarios called "Ensemble de Scénarios Polyvalents d'Ouranos” (ESPO) covering North America at a resolution of 0.1 degree (~9km). This operational product actually consists of two related datasets 1) ESPO-R (described here) produced from bias-adjusted regional climate simulations, and 2) ESPO-G produced following the same methodology, but from global simulations available via the CMIP program.
license: Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International Public License: https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/legalcode

In order to meet this growing demand and to ensure the availability of climate scenarios responding to numerous vulnerability, impact and adaptation (VIA) studies, Ouranos is working to create a set of operational multipurpose climate scenarios called "Ensemble de Scénarios Polyvalents d'Ouranos” (ESPO) covering North America at a resolution of 0.1 degree (~9km). This operational product actually consists of two related datasets 1) ESPO-R (described here) produced from bias-adjusted regional climate simulations, and 2) ESPO-G produced following the same methodology, but from global simulations available via the CMIP program.
license: Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International Public License: https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/legalcode

title: Climatedata.ca : CMIP6 : Climatic normal (30 year average) ensemble members for CanDCS-M6 derived climate indicators
institution: Canadian Centre for Climate Services
abstract: This dataset provides access to individual ensemble member CMIP6 climate indicator data that drives mapping and time-series visualizations on ClimateData.ca. Climatedata.ca is a climate data portal produced collaboratively by the country’s leading climate organizations and supported, in part, by the Government of Canada. The goal of this portal is to support decision makers across a broad spectrum of sectors and locations by providing the most up to date climate data in easy to use formats and visualizations.

title: ESPO-G6-E5L v1.0.0 : Ouranos Ensemble of Bias-adjusted Simulations - Global Models CMIP6 - ERA5-Land
institution: Ouranos Consortium on Regional Climatology and Adaptation to Climate Change
abstract: The need to adapt to climate change is present in a growing number of fields, leading to an increase in the demand for climate scenarios for often interrelated sectors of activity. In order to meet this growing demand and to ensure the availability of climate scenarios responding to numerous vulnerability, impact and adaptation (VIA) studies, Ouranos is working to create a set of operational bias-adjusted climate simulations called "Ensemble de simulations post-traitées d’Ouranos” (ESPO) covering North America.

abstract: The need to adapt to climate change is present in a growing number of fields, leading to an increase in the demand for climate scenarios for often interrelated sectors of activity. In order to meet this growing demand and to ensure the availability of climate scenarios responding to numerous vulnerability, impact and adaptation (VIA) studies, Ouranos is working to create a set of operational bias-adjusted climate simulations called "Ensemble de simulations post-traitées d’Ouranos” (ESPO) covering North America.
license: Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International Public License: https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/legalcode

institution: Ouranos Consortium on Regional Climatology and Adaptation to Climate Change
abstract: The need to adapt to climate change is present in a growing number of fields, leading to an increase in the demand for climate scenarios for often interrelated sectors of activity. In order to meet this growing demand and to ensure the availability of climate scenarios responding to numerous vulnerability, impact and adaptation (VIA) studies, Ouranos is working to create a set of operational bias-adjusted climate simulations called "Ensemble de simulations post-traitées d’Ouranos” (ESPO) covering North America.

In order to meet this growing demand and to ensure the availability of climate scenarios responding to numerous vulnerability, impact and adaptation (VIA) studies, Ouranos is working to create a set of operational bias-adjusted climate simulations called "Ensemble de simulations post-traitées d’Ouranos” (ESPO) covering North America.
license: Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International Public License: https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/legalcode

title: The ClimEx CRCM5 Large Ensemble
institution: Ouranos Consortium on Regional Climatology and Adaptation to Climate Change
abstract: The ClimEx CRCM5 Large Ensemble of high-resolution data for North-Eastern North America. This dataset consists of Canadian Regional Climate Model v.5 dynamically downscaled runs driven from 50 members of the CanESM2 GCM. The large ensemble with several thousand model years provides the potential to catch rare extreme events and improve the process understanding of extreme events with return periods of 100+ years.
